{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600773"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:07:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:07:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15631"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15631"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8322"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114394"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8322"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96395"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"},{"type":"tags","id":"8666"},{"type":"tags","id":"10132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23716"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114394"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe adrenal glands develop from multiple embryological tissue layers, with the cortex and medulla having distinct origins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological development of the adrenal cortex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Develops from neural crest cells that migrate to the urogenital ridge","Forms from intermediate mesoderm of the urogenital ridge","Differentiates from chromaffin cells during week 8","Develops after formation of the adrenal medulla","Originates from endoderm of the third pharyngeal pouch"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eintermediate mesoderm of the urogenital ridge\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to the adrenal cortex. This occurs around week 6 of development when mesenchymal cells proliferate and condense to form the primitive adrenal cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeural crest cells give rise to the adrenal medulla, not the cortex, whilst chromaffin cells form the medulla and derive from neural crest cells. The cortex forms first, with neural crest cells migrating through it later to form the medulla. The third pharyngeal pouch gives rise to the inferior parathyroid glands and thymus, not the adrenal cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe developing cortex later differentiates into the definitive cortex with its three distinct zones (glomerulosa, fasciculata, and reticularis) and the fetal zone, which is prominent during gestation but regresses after birth.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The adrenal cortex develops from intermediate mesoderm of the urogenital ridge","The adrenal cortex forms before the medulla during embryological development","The definitive cortex forms three distinct zones: glomerulosa, fasciculata, and reticularis"],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Torchia, M. G., \u0026 Persaud, T. V. N. (2020). Concise Clinical Embryology: an Integrated, Case-Based Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96395"}},"question":{"data":{"t